msgid "Benefits"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: /mnt/c/Users/etrees/Desktop/private/spring-framework/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/web/websocket/stomp/benefits.adoc:9
msgid ""
"Using STOMP as a sub-protocol lets the Spring Framework and Spring Security "
"provide a richer programming model versus using raw WebSockets. The same "
"point can be made about HTTP versus raw TCP and how it lets Spring MVC and "
"other web frameworks provide rich functionality. The following is a list of "
"benefits:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: /mnt/c/Users/etrees/Desktop/private/spring-framework/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/web/websocket/stomp/benefits.adoc:11
msgid "No need to invent a custom messaging protocol and message format."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: /mnt/c/Users/etrees/Desktop/private/spring-framework/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/web/websocket/stomp/benefits.adoc:13
msgid ""
"STOMP clients, including a xref:web/websocket/stomp/client.adoc[Java client] "
"in the Spring Framework, are available."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: /mnt/c/Users/etrees/Desktop/private/spring-framework/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/web/websocket/stomp/benefits.adoc:15
msgid ""
"You can (optionally) use message brokers (such as RabbitMQ, ActiveMQ, and "
"others) to manage subscriptions and broadcast messages."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: /mnt/c/Users/etrees/Desktop/private/spring-framework/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/web/websocket/stomp/benefits.adoc:18
msgid ""
"Application logic can be organized in any number of `@Controller` instances "
"and messages can be routed to them based on the STOMP destination header "
"versus handling raw WebSocket messages with a single `WebSocketHandler` for "
"a given connection."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: /mnt/c/Users/etrees/Desktop/private/spring-framework/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/web/websocket/stomp/benefits.adoc:18
msgid ""
"You can use Spring Security to secure messages based on STOMP destinations "
"and message types."
msgstr ""
